	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Oct 15th 6:03 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[4.32]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Dude, I've just gotta flame you for this. I can see how AGI would be good for warriors, although STA might be more important for them, because they're tanks; it's their job to know how to take damage. The rogue's job is to DO damage. They can do the most melee damage of any class in the game and quite possibly the most damage of any class overall if you know what you're doing and play it right. Which means forget about AGI and AC. Everyone keeps saying that STR and DEX items are easy to come by. SO WHAT? You can never have too much STR and DEX, so why not start with higher anyway? Nobody seems to notice that AC and AGI are even easier to come by. Obviously, AC comes with pretty much any armor you'll actually wear, and AGI comes along with most of the DEX pieces I wear. I've got +49 in DEX items, and +20 AGI came with it, without even looking for AGI items. By the time I fight mobs w/ 32k HP, I doubt I will be doing only 300 extra damage than others. I do 100-200 more damage than others in my group right NOW, and often I do more than everyone else put together (not counting casters of course cuz I couldn't see how much they hit for, but once I had a pally, a tank, and a monk, all higher lvl than me, who couldn't match my damage together) And at the same time, I doubt I would take more damage than others. Unless something goes terribly wrong and all the tanks die, I won't take more than a scratch cuz evade (evade works off of hide, which is guess what...a DEX skill). Even then there are monks and other rogues and whatnot who will probably get picked on first. So unless you're planning on soloing the deities and dragons of the world, forget AGI.<br>&nbsp;<br>Daviv McD 28th Dwarf Rogue<br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=13233" target=_new>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=13233</a></td></tr>
