	   <tr><td colspan=2>In addition to that, cuz I was running out of time while I wrote it, you try to assume too much about me. I originally picked a rogue cuz I thought they looked cool, with all the cool skills they could do. I thought it would be nice to go around sneaking and hiding and role-playing that I was above the common folk and I had advantages over all the folk and stuff like that. It wasn't til later that I realized that rogues actually rocked, and it was later yet when I realized that rogues are one of the main damage dealers in combat. I wouldn't want to role-play a caster except maybe a hybrid because frankly in role-playing terms they are wusses, always staying back from the main combat and letting their nukes/pets do the work for them. If you actually read any fantasy books you'll find that the casters are generally better in combat overall, making them the most powerful kind of characters. Well anyway I don't really play to role-play that much, and I don't play to be a "power gamer" or whatever other kind of crap you wanna label me with, I just play to have fun. Heh here's something to ponder, you admit that the rogue's job is to do damage, and then you say that str/dex isn't the only part of the equation. So ummm, how does AGI fit into the damage equation? Cuz that's what you were arguing. Doesn't make much sense to me.<br><br>Daviv McD &lt;Fearless Empire&gt;<br>26th Dwarf Rogue<br>Xegony<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
